Trade tariffs aid a handful of aluminum and steel producers and hurts hundreds of industries and most importantly the consumer. Market/economic risks are rising. And I suspect Gary Cohn will be gone shortly.

and a driver or engine of global economic growth? With G-8's geopolitical coordination at an all-time low, how slow and inept will the reaction be if the wheels do come off? As I wrote, I don't have answers but I am increasingly fearful of rising political and geopolitical risks.

Remember several of my questions that I ask myself everyday: In a paperless and cloudy world, are investors and citizens as safe as the markets assume we are? In a flat, networked and interconnected world, is it even possible for America to be an "oasis of prosperity"

From my opener on @TSTRealMoneyPro : This means that it will be increasingly difficult to ascertain what the effect on world wide economic growth will be. My guess, for now, is that it will be a magnitude that none of us can compute.
The timing is also difficult to predict -- but I believe political and geopolitical headwinds are likely creeping up on investors (and the world)."
This is a very subjective issue but I believe we are seeing an unraveling (a dysfunctional White House, the potential for trade wars, terrorism, etc.) that is not currently priced into the markets.
